[Download RAW <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837781926950&q=mbox">message</a> or <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837781926950&q=raw">body</a>]</b>

Seems to me that the domain system could be a great testbed for
experiments in adaptive network algorithms.  A resolver wishes
to retrieve records which it knows are stored in N servers at
different locations.  It wishes to minimize both its wait for the
data, and its impact upon the network.  What is its optimum policy?
Sending out N queries will get it the response in minimal time, but
also with a large cost in network resources.  Conversely, with one
query it may have to wait a long time, but it will have minimal
impact on the network.  A number of intermediate approaches are
possible, such as choosing M &lt; N random servers to query, or
choosing the M &lt; N servers whose response has been fastest in the
past, or choosing the M servers with fastest past performance plus
K random servers as experiments (M+K&lt;N).  Timing information could
be cached in a server's local database.  Is anyone working on this?
It doesn't seem so tough.

Peter
